N:langextract
D:Extract structured, source-grounded information from unstructured text with LangExtract. Use when the job is entity or relationship extraction from text, notes, reports, URLs, or long documents and the user wants grounded spans back to the source. Supports Gemini, OpenAI, Ollama, and custom providers.
G:langextract information-extraction nlp ner entity-extraction structured-output gemini openai ollama grounding provenance document-parsing text-mining

U[7]:
  Extract named entities with grounded spans from text, URLs, notes, and reports
  Process clinical notes, contracts, or research papers into structured data
  Build schema-guided extraction pipelines with high-quality few-shot examples
  Handle long documents with chunking, parallel workers, and multi-pass extraction
  Filter out ungrounded example leakage with char_interval checks
  Run private local extraction with Ollama and no API key
  Extend LangExtract with explicit provider routing or plugin-style providers

S[6]{n,action,details}:
  1,Check boundary,Use LangExtract only after the source is available as clean text or a retrievable URL; do OCR or PDF parsing first when needed
  2,Define schema,Create ExampleData objects with ordered verbatim extraction_text spans and attributes so the examples define the schema cleanly
  3,Extract,Call lx.extract(text_or_documents=..., prompt_description=..., examples=..., model_id="gemini-2.5-flash") for the default Gemini path
  4,Provider choice,For OpenAI or Ollama keep fence_output and use_schema_constraints unset by default; for custom routing use ModelConfig and an explicit provider
  5,Grounding filter,Drop extractions with char_interval=None when you need strictly grounded outputs from the source text only
  6,Scale and review,Use extraction_passes=3 + max_workers + max_char_buffer for long docs, then save JSONL and generate HTML with lx.visualize()

R[5]:
  Write precise prompts such as "use exact text" when grounded spans matter
  Use 2-3 strong ExampleData cases instead of adding many weak examples
  Filter on char_interval when strict grounding matters more than raw recall
  Use max_char_buffer=500-1000 and extraction_passes=3 for long-document coverage
  Keep OCR and raw document parsing outside this skill; feed it normalized text first

E[4]{desc,in,out}:
  "Basic entity extraction","lx.extract(text='Patient took 10mg aspirin daily', prompt_description='Extract medications and dosages', examples=[...], model_id='gemini-2.5-flash')","Extraction(extraction_class='medication', extraction_text='aspirin', start=16, end=23, attributes={'dosage': '10mg', 'frequency': 'daily'})"
  "Long document from URL","lx.extract(text_or_documents='https://gutenberg.org/files/1513/1513-0.txt', ..., extraction_passes=3, max_workers=20)","4088 entities extracted from Romeo & Juliet (147k chars) — characters, emotions, relationships with offsets"
  "Local LLM via Ollama","lx.extract(..., model_id='gemma2:2b', model_url='http://localhost:11434')","Same extraction interface with fully local model — no API key required and provider defaults stay auto-configured"
  "Grounded review loop","grounded = [e for e in result.extractions if e.char_interval]; lx.io.save_annotated_documents([result], 'results.jsonl')","Strictly grounded outputs plus a color-coded HTML review artifact over the source text"
